{{For|other nomadic polities often called "Huns"|Xiongnu|Kidarites|Hephthalites|Alchon Huns|Nezak Huns|Sabirs|Utigurs|Kutrigurs|Khazars}}
{{other uses|Hun (disambiguation)|Hunnic (disambiguation)|Hunnic language}}
{{pp-move-indef}}

The '''Huns''' were a [[nomadic people]] who lived in [[Central Asia]], the [[Caucasus]], and [[Eastern Europe]], between the 4th and 6th century AD. According to European tradition, they were first reported living east of the [[Volga River]], in an area that was part of [[Scythia]] at the time; the Huns' arrival is associated with the migration westward of a [[Scythians|Scythian]] people, the [[Alans]].{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}} By 370 AD, the Huns had arrived on the Volga, and by 430 the Huns had established a vast, if short-lived, dominion in Europe.

In the 18th century, the French scholar [[Joseph de Guignes]] became the first to propose a link between the Huns and the [[Xiongnu]] people, who [[History of the Han Dynasty|were northern neighbours]] of [[China]] in the 3rd century BC.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=175, 180}}{{sfn|Grousset|1970}} Since Guignes' time, considerable scholarly effort has been devoted to investigating such a connection. However, there is no scholarly consensus on a direct connection between the dominant element of the Xiongnu and that of the Huns.{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}} [[Priscus]], a 5th-century [[Eastern Roman Empire|Roman]] diplomat and historian, mentions that the Huns had a [[Hunnic language|language of their own]]; little of it has survived and scholars have considered whether it was related to [[Turkic languages|Turkic]], [[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]], or even [[Tungusic languages|Tungusic]] language families, although the almost complete lack of a text corpus renders the language [[unclassified languages|unclassifiable]] at present. Some researchers indeed argue, the original Huns may have had a [[Yeniseian]] tribal elite, which ruled initially over various Turkic, Mongolic, and Iranian-speaking tribes.{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=29}} Numerous other ethnic groups were included under [[Attila|Attila the Hun]]'s rule, including very many speakers of [[Gothic language|Gothic]], which some modern scholars describe as a [[lingua franca]] of the Empire.{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=228}} Their main military technique was [[mounted archery]].

The Huns may have stimulated the [[Migration Period|Great Migration]], a contributing factor in the collapse of the [[Western Roman Empire]].{{sfn|Ammianus|1939|loc=Ch. 2|ps=: However, the seed and origin of all the ruin and various disasters that the wrath of Mars aroused&nbsp;... we have found to be (the invasions of the Huns)}} They formed a unified empire under [[Attila|Attila the Hun]], who died in 453; after a defeat at the [[Battle of Nedao]] their empire disintegrated over the next 15 years. Their descendants, or successors with similar names, are recorded by neighbouring populations to the south, east and west as having occupied parts of [[Eastern Europe]] and Central Asia from about the 4th to 6th centuries. Variants of the Hun name are recorded in the Caucasus until the early 8th century. The memory of the Huns also lived on in various Christian [[hagiography|saints' lives]], where the Huns play the roles of antagonists, as well as in Germanic heroic legend, where the Huns are variously antagonists or allies to the Germanic main figures. In Hungary, a legend developed based on medieval chronicles that the [[Hungarians]], and the [[Székely]] ethnic group in particular, are descended from the Huns. However, mainstream scholarship dismisses a close connection between the Hungarians and Huns.{{sfn|Szűcs|1999|p=xliv}}{{sfn|Engel|2002|p=2}}{{sfn|Lendvai|2003|p=7}}{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=386}}

== Origin ==
[[File:Eurasian steppe belt.jpg|thumb|The [[Eurasian Steppe]] Belt (in {{Colorsample|#AAEEFF}} on the map).]]

The Huns were "a confederation of warrior bands",{{attribution needed|date=March 2018}} ready to integrate other groups to increase their military power, in the [[Eurasian Steppe]] in the 4th to {{nobr|6th centuries AD}}.{{sfn|Pohl|1999|pp=501–502}} Most aspects of their [[ethnogenesis]] (including their language and their links to other peoples of the steppes) are uncertain.{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=502}}{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=176}} [[Walter Pohl]] states: "All we can say safely is that the name ''Huns'', in [[late antiquity]], described prestigious ruling groups of steppe warriors."{{sfn|Pohl|1999|p=502}}

[[File:Hsiung-nu-Empire.png|thumb|left|Domain and influence of [[Xiongnu]] under [[Modu Chanyu]] around 205 BC, the believed place of Huns' origin.]]

The Roman historian [[Ammianus Marcellinus]], who completed his work of the history of the [[Roman Empire]] in the early 390s, recorded that the "people of the {{nobr|Huns …}} dwell beyond the [[Sea of Azov]] near the frozen ocean".<ref name=Ammianus_Marcellinus_31.2_411>''Ammianus Marcellinus: The Later Roman Empire'' (31.2.), p. 411.</ref>{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=177}} [[Jerome]] associated them with the [[Scythians]]  in a letter, written four years after the Huns invaded the empire's eastern provinces in 395.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=4}} The equation of the Huns with the Scythians, together with a general fear of the coming of the [[Antichrist]] in the late {{nobr|4th century}}, gave rise to their identification with [[Gog and Magog]] (whom [[Alexander the Great]] had shut off behind inaccessible mountains, according to a popular legend).{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|pp=2–4}} This demonization of the Huns is also reflected in [[Jordanes]]'s ''[[Getica]]'', written in the {{nobr|6th century}}, which portrayed them as a people descending from "[[demon|unclean spirits]]"<ref>''The Gothic History of Jordanes'' (24:121), p. 85.</ref> and expelled [[Goths|Gothic]] witches.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=5}}{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=209}}

Since [[Joseph de Guignes]] in the {{nobr|18th century}}, modern historians have associated the Huns who appeared on the borders of Europe in the {{nobr|4th century AD}} with the [[Xiongnu]] who had invaded China from the territory of present-day [[Mongolia]] between the {{nobr|3rd century BC}} and the {{nobr|2nd century AD}}.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=175, 180}}{{sfn|Grousset|1970}} Due to the [[Han–Xiongnu War|devastating defeat by the Chinese Han dynasty]], the northern branch of the Xiongnu had retreated north-westward; their descendants may have migrated through [[Eurasia]] and consequently they may have some degree of cultural and genetic continuity with the Huns.{{sfn|Wright|2011|p=60}} [[Otto J. Maenchen-Helfen]] was the first to challenge the traditional approach, based primarily on the study of written sources, and to emphasize the importance of archaeological research.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=175}} Thereafter the identification of the Xiongnu as the Huns' ancestors became controversial among some.{{sfn|Wright|2011|p=60}}

[[File:Klosz Gyorgy hun.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|A Hunnish [[cauldron]]]]

The similarity of their ethnonyms is one of the most important links between the two peoples.{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}} The [[Buddhist]] monk [[Dharmarakṣa]], who was an important translator of [[India]]n religious texts in the {{nobr|3rd century AD}}, applied the word Xiongnu when translating the references to the [[Huna people]] into Chinese.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=179}} According to [[Zhengzhang Shangfang]], ''Xiongnu'' was pronounced [hoŋ.naː] in Late [[Old Chinese]], corresponding well to ''Huna''.{{sfn|Zhengzhang|2003|p=429,505}} A [[Sogdia]]n merchant described the invasion of northern China by the "''Xwn''" people in a letter, written in {{nobr|313 AD}}.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=179}} [[Étienne de la Vaissière]] asserts both documents prove that ''Huna'' or ''Xwn'' were the "exact transcriptions" of the Chinese "Xiongnu" name.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=181}} Christopher P. Atwood rejects de la Vassiere's particular etymological interpretation because of the "very poor phonological match" between the three words.{{sfn|Atwood|2012|p=27}} He instead argues that because ''Xiongnu'' begins with a velar spirant and ''Huna'' with a glottal spirant, and that ''Xiongnu'' is a two-syllable word, but ''Xwn'' only has one syllable. However, Atwood agrees with the overall idenfitication between the two, showing instead that ''Xwn'' and Greek ''Khōnai'' comes via Chinese transcription of ''Huní'', while Sanskrit ''Huna'' comes from the transcription of Chinese ''Xiongnu'' in the 2nd or 1st century BC due to the fact Sanskrit cannot render a velar spirant or a velar nasal. He argues it was ultimately transmitted from Sanskrit to Baktrian Greek, where it became ''Ounna'' (evidenced via John Malalas and the Chinese form ''Wēnnàshā'' in the ''Wei Shu''), as Greek cannot render a retroflex dental nasal like Sanskrit, becoming a coronal dental nasal. Likewise, he argues the glottal spirant was also lost in transcription to Baktrian Greek, since Greek tends to drop the glottal spirant, and instead became a glottal stop. Merchants then took it to the Kuban region, where it took the forms ''Ounnoi'' and ''Hunni'' in Roman Greek and Latin.{{sfn|Atwood|2012|p=28-48}} The Chinese ''[[Book of Wei]]'' also contain references to "the remains of the descendants of the Xiongnu" who lived in the region of the [[Altai Mountains]] in the early {{nobr|5th century AD}}.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=188}} According to De la Vaissière, the Central Asian and Chinese sources prove that the Hunnic nomadic group preserved their Xiongnu identity for centuries after their movement west.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=188}}

Both the Xiongnu and Huns used bronze cauldrons, similarly to all peoples of the steppes.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=187}} Based on the study and categorization of cauldrons from archaeological sites of the Eurasian Steppes, archaeologist Toshio Hayashi concludes that the spread of the cauldrons "may indicate the route of migration of the Hunnic tribes" from Mongolia to the northern region of Central Asia in the 2nd or {{nobr|3rd century AD}}, and from Central Asia towards Europe in the second half of the {{nobr|4th century}}, which also implies the Huns' association with the Xiongnu.{{sfn|Hayashi|2014|p=16}} This custom had already been practised in the Eurasian Steppes in the [[Bronze Age]] and in the early [[Iron Age]], but it disappeared around {{nobr|500 BC}}.{{sfn|Molnár|János|Szűcs|Szathmáry|2014}} It again started to spread among the local inhabitants of the region of the [[Talas River]] and in the [[Pamir Mountains]] in the {{nobr|1st century BC}}.{{sfn|Molnár|János|Szűcs|Szathmáry|2014}} In addition to the Huns, the custom is also evidenced among the [[Yuezhi]] and [[Alans]].{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=33, 39}} The lengthy pony-tail, which was a characteristic of the Xiongnu, was not documented among the Huns.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}}

[[File:Gold monster.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|A gold stag with eagle's head, and ten further heads in the antlers. From a Xiongnu tomb on the frontier, 4th-3rd century BC]]

When writing of the relationship between the Xiongnu and Huns, historian Hyun Jin Kim concludes: "Thus to refer to Hun-Xiongnu links in terms of old racial theories or even ethnic affiliations simply makes a mockery of the actual historical reality of these extensive, multiethnic, polyglot steppe empires".{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=31}} He also emphasizes that "the ancestors of the Hunnic core {{nobr|tribes …}} were part of the Xiongnu Empire and possessed a strong Xiongnu element, and the ruling elite of the {{nobr|Huns …}} claimed to belong to the political tradition of this imperial entity."{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=31}} Nevertheless he claims: "Huns seem to have had a core Turkic element, ruling over initially a large Turco-Iranian population."{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=29}} Taking into account the historical gap between the Chinese reports of the Xiongnu and the European records of the Huns, [[Peter Heather]] states: "Even if we do make some connection between fourth-century Huns and first-century [Xiongnu], therefore, an awful lot of water had passed under an awful lot of bridges during 300 years worth of lost history."{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}}

==History==

=== Before Attila ===
[[File:Hunnenwanderung.png|thumb|A suggested path of the Huns' movement westwards (labels in German)]]

The 2nd century geographer [[Ptolemy]] mentioned a people called Χοῦνοι ''Khunnoi'',{{sfn|Kim|2013|p=209}}{{sfn|Kim|2015|p=66}}  when listing the peoples of the west Eurasian steppe.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=447}}{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=25}} (In the [[Koine Greek]] used by Ptolemy, [[Χ]] generally denoted a [[voiceless velar fricative]] sound; hence contemporary [[Western Roman Empire|Western Roman]] authors [[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] the name as ''Chuni'' or ''Chunni''.) The ''Khunnoi'' lived "between the [[Bastarnae]] and the [[Roxolani]]", according to Ptolemy.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=447}}{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=25}} However, modern scholars such as [[Edward Arthur Thompson|E. A. Thompson]] have claimed that the similarity of the ethnonyms ''Khunnoi'' and Hun were coincidental.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=25}} Maenchen-Helfen and [[Denis Sinor]] also dispute the association of the ''Khunnoi'' with Attila's Huns.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=449}} However, Maenchen-Helfen concedes that Ammianus Marcellinus referred to Ptolemy's report of the ''Khunnoi'', when stating that the Huns were "mentioned only cursorily" by previous writers.<ref name=Ammianus_Marcellinus_31.2_411/>{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=449}}

A tribe called the Ουρουγούνδοι ''Ourougoúndoi'' (or ''Urugundi'') whom, according to [[Zosimus]],  invaded the Roman Empire from north of the [[Lower Danube]] in {{nobr|250 AD}} may have been synonymous with the Βουρουγουνδοι ''Bourougoundoi'', whom [[Agathias]] (6th century) listed among the Hunnish tribes.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|pp=452–453}} Other scholars have regarded both names as referring to a Germanic tribe, the [[Burgundians|Burgundi]] (Burgundians), although this identification was rejected by Maenchen-Helfen (who speculated that one or both names may have approximated an [[Turkic_languages#History|early Turkic]] ethnonym, such as "''Vurugundi''").{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|pp=452–453}}

The Romans became aware of the Huns when the latter's invasion of the [[Pontic steppes]] forced thousands of Goths to move to the Lower Danube to seek refuge in the Roman Empire in 376, according to the contemporaneous Ammianus Marcellinus.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Their sudden appearance in the written sources suggests that the Huns crossed the [[Volga River]] from the east not much earlier.{{sfn|de la Vaissière|2015|p=177}} They invaded the land of the [[Alans]], which was located to the east of the [[Don River (Russia)|Don River]], slaughtering many of them and forcing the survivors to submit themselves to them or to flee across the Don.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|pp=26–27}}{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=215}}{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=19}} The reasons for the Huns' sudden attack on the neighboring peoples have long believed to be unknown.{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=212}} However, recent research has shown that the [[El Niño–Southern Oscillation|El Nino Southern Oscillation]] caused a megadrought in 360, which spurred Inner Asian migration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cook|first=Edward|date=2013|title=Megadroughts, ENSO, and the Invasion of Late-Roman Europe by the Huns and Avars|url=|journal=The Ancient Mediterranean Environment: Between Science and History|volume=|pages=89–102|via=}}</ref>

After they subjugated the Alans, the Huns and their Alan auxiliaries started plundering the wealthy settlements of the [[Greuthungi]], or eastern [[Goths]], to the west of the Don.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} The Greuthungic king, [[Ermanaric]], resisted for a while, but finally "he found release from his fears by taking his own life",{{sfn|Ammianus|602|p=415}} according to Ammianus Marcellinus.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Marcellinus's report refers either to Ermanaric's suicide{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=27}} or to his [[Human sacrifice|ritual sacrifice]].{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} His great-nephew, [[Vithimiris]], succeeded him.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=27}} He hired Huns to fight against the Alans who invaded the Greuthungi's land, but he was killed in a battle.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=27}}{{sfn|Heather|2010|p=215}}

[[File:Hunnerkrigare.jpg|thumb|left|''Hun warriors''. Colored engraving from 1890.]]

After Vithimiris's death, most Greuthungi submitted themselves to the Huns.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=27}} Those who decided to resist marched to the [[Dniester River]] which was the border between the lands of the Greuthungi and the [[Thervingi]], or western Goths.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=28}} They were under the command of [[Alatheus]] and [[Saphrax]], because Vithimiris's son, Viderichus, was a child.{{sfn|Thompson|1996|p=28}} [[Athanaric]], the leader of the Thervingi, met the refugees along the Dniester at the head of his troops.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} However, a Hun army bypassed the Goths and attacked them from the rear, forcing Athanaric to retreat towards the [[Carpathian Mountains]].{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Athanaric wanted to fortify the borders, but Hun raids into the land west of the Dniester continued.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Most Thervingi realized that they could not resist the Huns.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} They went to the Lower Danube, requesting asylum in the Roman Empire.{{sfn|James|2009|p=51}} The Greuthingi under the leadership of Alatheus and Saphrax also marched to the river.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Most Roman troops had been transferred from the [[Balkan Peninsula]] to fight against the [[Sassanid Empire]] in [[Armenia]].{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}} Emperor [[Valens]] permitted the Thervingi to cross the Lower Danube and to settle in the Roman Empire in the autumn of 376.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=26}} The Thervingi were followed by the Greuthingi, and also by the [[Taifali]] and "other tribes that formerly dwelt with the Goths and Taifali" to the north of the Lower Danube, according to Zosimus.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=26}} Food shortage and abuse stirred the Goths to revolt in early 377.{{sfn|James|2009|p=51}} The ensuing war between the Goths and the Romans lasted for more than five years.{{sfn|Heather|2005|pp=146–167}}

[[File:Invasions of the Roman Empire 1.png|thumb|left|The [[Barbarian invasions]] of the 5th century were triggered by the destruction of the Gothic kingdoms by the Huns in 372–375. The city of Rome was captured and looted by the [[Visigoths]] in 410 and by the [[Vandals]] in 455.]]

Support for the Gothic chieftains diminished as refugees headed into [[Thrace]] and towards the safety of the Roman garrisons.

After these invasions, the Huns begin to be noted as [[Foederati]] and mercenaries. As early as 380, a group of Huns was given Foederati status and allowed to settle in [[Pannonia]]. Hunnish mercenaries were also seen on several occasions in the succession struggles of the Eastern and Western Roman Empire during the late 4th century. However, it is most likely that these were individual mercenary bands, not a Hunnish kingdom.{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}}

[[File:Hunnish - Bracelet - Walters 571082 - Detail Front.jpg|thumb|Detail of Hunnish gold and garnet bracelet, 5th century, [[Walters Art Museum]]]]

[[File:Hunnish - Fibula - Walters 57558.jpg|thumb|An Hunnish oval openwork fibula set with a carnelian and decorated with a geometric pattern of gold wire, 4th century, [[Walters Art Museum]]]]

In 395 the Huns began their first large-scale attack on the Eastern Roman Empire.{{sfn|Thompson|1948}} Huns attacked in Thrace, overran [[Armenia]], and pillaged [[Cappadocia]]. They entered parts of [[Syria]], threatened [[Antioch]], and swarmed through the province of [[Euphratesia]]. The forces of [[Theodosius I|Emperor Theodosius]] were fully committed in the west so the Huns moved unopposed until the end of 398 when the eunuch [[Eutropius (Byzantine official)|Eutropius]] gathered together a force composed of Romans and Goths and succeeded in restoring peace. It is uncertain though, whether or not Eutropius' forces defeated the Huns or whether the Huns left on their own. There is no record of a notable victory by Eutropius and there is evidence that the Hunnish forces were already leaving the area by the time he gathered his forces.{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}}

Whether put to flight by Eutropius, or leaving on their own, the Huns had left the Eastern Roman Empire by 398. After this, the Huns invaded the Sassanid Empire. This invasion was initially successful, coming close to the capital of the empire at [[Ctesiphon]]; however, they were defeated badly during the [[Persian Empire|Persian]] counterattack and retreated toward the [[Caucasus Mountains]] via the [[Derbent|Derbend Pass]].{{sfn|Sinor|1990|pp=177–203}}

During their brief diversion from the [[Eastern Roman]] Empire, the Huns appear to have threatened tribes further west, as evidenced by [[Radagaisus]]' entering Italy at the end of 405 and the [[Crossing of the Rhine|crossing of the Rhine into Gaul]] by [[Vandals]], [[Suebi|Sueves]], and Alans in 406.{{sfn|Thompson|1948}} The Huns do not then appear to have been a single force with a single ruler. Many Huns were employed as mercenaries by both East and West Romans and by the Goths. [[Uldin]], the first Hun known by name,{{sfn|Thompson|1948}} headed a group of Huns and Alans fighting against Radagaisus in defense of Italy. Uldin was also known for defeating Gothic rebels giving trouble to the East Romans around the Danube and beheading the Goth [[Gainas]] around 400–401. Gainas' head was given to the East Romans for display in Constantinople in an apparent exchange of gifts.

The East Romans began to feel the pressure from Uldin's Huns again in 408. Uldin crossed the Danube and captured a fortress in [[Moesia]] named Castra Martis, which was betrayed from within. Uldin then proceeded to ransack Thrace. The East Romans tried to buy Uldin off, but his sum was too high so they instead bought off Uldin's subordinates. This resulted in many desertions from Uldin's group of Huns.

[[Alaric I|Alaric's]] brother-in-law, [[Athaulf]], appears to have had Hun mercenaries in his employ south of the [[Julian Alps]] in 409. These were countered by another small band of Huns hired by [[Honorius (emperor)|Honorius']] minister Olympius. Later in 409, the West Romans stationed ten thousand Huns in Italy and [[Dalmatia]] to fend off Alaric, who then abandoned plans to march on Rome, and in 433 some parts of [[Pannonia]] were ceded to them by [[Flavius Aetius]], the [[magister militum]] of the [[Western Roman Empire]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.sk/books?id=ST6TRNuWmHsC&pg=PA187&dq=huns++Pannonia+++Aetius++433&hl=cs&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn396H-KjeAhXQzqQKHeCUCCwQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=huns%20%20Pannonia%20%20%20Aetius%20%20433&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of Early Inner Asia – Google Knihy |publisher=Books.google.cz |date=1990 |accessdate=2018-10-28 |isbn=0-521-24304-1}}</ref>

=== Under Attila and Bleda ===

[[File:Brogi, Carlo (1850-1925) - n. 8227 - Certosa di Pavia - Medaglione sullo zoccolo della facciata.jpg|thumb|left|A nineteenth century depiction of Attila. [[Certosa di Pavia]] - Medallion at the base of the facade. The Latin inscription tells that this is Attila, the scourge of God.]]

From 434 the brothers [[Attila]] and [[Bleda]] ruled the Huns together. Attila and Bleda were as ambitious as their uncle [[Rugila]]. In 435 they forced the Eastern Roman Empire to sign the [[Treaty of Margus]],{{sfn|Thompson|1999|p=136}} giving the Huns trade rights and an annual tribute from the Romans. The Romans also agreed to give up Hunnic refugees (individuals who could have threatened the brothers' grip on power) for execution. With their southern border protected by the terms of this treaty, the Huns could turn their full attention to the further subjugation of tribes to the west.

When the Romans breached the treaty in 440, Attila and Bleda attacked Castra Constantias, a Roman fortress and marketplace on the banks of the [[Danube]].{{sfn|Harvey|2003|p=15}} The Eastern Romans stopped delivery of the agreed tribute, and they broke other conditions of the Treaty of Margus. The Hunnic kings turned their attention back to the Eastern Romans. Reports that the Bishop of Margus had crossed into Hun lands and desecrated royal graves further angered the Hun kings. War broke out between the two empires, and the Huns overcame a weak [[Roman army]] to raze the cities of Margus, [[Singidunum]] and [[Viminacium]]. Although a truce was signed in 441, two years later [[Constantinople]] again failed to deliver the tribute and war resumed. In the following campaign, Hun armies came alarmingly close to Constantinople, sacking [[Sardica]], [[Arcadiopolis in Europa|Arcadiopolis]] and [[Plovdiv|Philippopolis]] along the way. Suffering a complete defeat at the [[Gallipoli|Battle of Chersonesus]], the Eastern Roman Emperor [[Theodosius II]] gave in to Hun demands and in autumn 443 signed the [[Peace of Anatolius]] with the two Hun kings. The Huns returned to their lands with a vast train full of plunder.

